habitat_description:
This species is excluded from the Washington Cascade Mountains and occupies the southwestern corner of Washington State south into western Oregon to include the Cascade Range (Storm and Brodie 1970; Leonard et al. 1993; Lannoo 2005), and a limited area in Del Norte County in California (Bury et al. 1969). In Oregon, this species occurs from the high tide line of the Pacific Ocean throughout the Coast Range and into the west flank of the Cascades at an elevation of about 1000 meters (Nussbaum et al. 1983; Petranka 1998; Green et al. 2013; Stebbins 2003). It is important to note that this species is absent from the lower parts of the Willamette Valley (Storm and Brodie 1970). 

In the Coast Range, this species is associated with shale outcrops or sandstones near seeps, streams, and springs (Dumas 1956). Populations in the Cascades are associated with basaltic talus near seeps, streams, and springs, and individuals are often observed in wet rocky areas (Nussbaum et al. 1983). Bury et al. (1991) have reported that although this species co-occurs with torrent salamanders (Rhyacotriton sp.), Dunn’s salamanders are more frequently captured along stream banks.
